ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 1
 presents a schematic representation of the synthetic process of the CD-based bimetallic nanocomposites (CDCoNi-n, n = 1, 2, and 3). Cobalt acetate and Nickel acetate salts were the metal precursors, whereas CDs were the structure-directing template towards the formation of a layered structure. The concentration of CDs was varied to achieve the optimized conditions. Under the present experimental conditions, the optimized concentration of CDs (1 mg mL−1) produced solid metal composite particles that could be separated from the solution for future use. This synthetic process followed a low temperature hydrothermal treatment that produced the metal double hydroxides. The X-ray diffraction (XRD) pattern, within a range of 10–80°, of the three samples revealed the formation of Ni(OH)2 and Co(OH)2 (Fig. 2
) [22,24]. XRD peaks at 31.2°, 36°, 55.3°, and 59° were corresponded to (100), (101), (102), and (110) planes of β-phase [34,35] of CDCoNi-n double hydroxides [JCPDS No. 38–0715 and 02–0925]. The peaks contained contribution from Co and Ni-hydroxides, but the close position of these peaks did not allow distinguishing the peaks separately. The results were in accordance with the previous results [34]. The peaks of three different composites were different due to alteration in metal concentration. The sharpness of the metal peaks indicated crystallinity. A broad peak for carbon was observed over the 2θ range, 22°–25°. The peak indicated the existence of carbon plane [36]. XRD analysis of the CD particles was also performed to examine the origin of the carbon source in metal composite. As in Fig. S1, peaks centered at 2θ = 22.5° and 42°, corresponding to the (002) and (100) plane of hexagonal graphitic carbon, respectively, were observed [37]. Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectroscopy (Fig. 2) was performed over a range of 4000–600 cm−1 to examine the functional groups on the nanocomposites. The broad peak at 3323 cm−1 and the peak at 1236 cm−1 were assigned to the -O-H stretching and bending vibrations, respectively. The absorbance peaks at 2975 cm−1 and 2868 cm−1 were assigned to the –CH2-stretching vibration. The peak at 1375 cm−1 was assigned to the C–N bond whereas the -N-H bending vibration occurred at 875 cm−1. The peak at 875 cm−1 could be assigned to the = C–H out of plane bending vibration [38,39]. The -C-O and -C-O-C- stretching bonds were observed at 1094 cm−1 for 1038 cm−1, respectively, for CDCoNi-n particles [40,41]. The peak intensities differed according to the different concentration of elements. FTIR spectroscopy of CDs revealed the presence of similar functional groups (Fig. S1). Peaks at 3450, ∼2976, 1658, 1540, 1457, 1040, and 879 cm−1 represented the -N-H/-O-H stretching, –CH2- stretching, –CO, -O-H bending, -C-N stretching, -C-O-C, and imidazole -N-H/ = C–H out of lane bending, respectively [42,43]. The XRD and FTIR peaks confirmed the association of CDs with the metal counterpart. The functional groups present on the CD surface interacted with the metals.
